title.narrative: Strengthened management of external audit capacity by the extent of audit coverage in line with international audit standards and no. of audit reports submitted to the National Assembly.

baseline.value: Low level of audit coverage of public entities and operations. No published audit reports to date.

target.value: Audit coverage of at least 50% of government expenditures. Government annual financial statements audit report published.

title.narrative: Strengthened management of public resources as measured by more credible budget formulation & implementation and reduced fiduciary risk.

baseline.value: 2001-2003 Average quarterly outturn as percentage of budget . [Q1:7%; Q2:18%; Q3:36% and Q4:64%]. Weighted average of publicprocurement price differential greater than 20%Percentage of payments to creditors in 2005: 5%Percentage of tax revenue collectedthrough banking system in 2005: 2%.Outstanding arrears: riel 554 billion

target.value: the end of each Quarter. [Q1:15%; Q2:40%; Q3:70% and Q4:90%]. Reduction in price differential to 15% of market price.

actual.value: The end of Q1 2013 19%. The whole 2012 [Q1: 12.5%, Q2:36.5%, Q3:61.9%, Q4:100.3%]Payment through banking system: 67.77% in 2012;39 ministries used bank account for salary payment; Revenue collection through banking system: Custom revenue 100% and Taxrevenue 99%; no payment arrears.

comment.narrative: Further improved commitment and payment processes.

title.narrative: Strengthened mobilization of public resources as measured by increases in tax and non-tax revenues as a percentage of GDP.

baseline.value: 2005 Revenue as %GDP 10.3% of which Tax 7.6% and Non Tax 2.2%.Direct tax 3%Indirect tax 9%

target.value: Annual revenue-to-GDP ratio 0.5 percent per annum

actual.value: Revenue by Q1 2013 achieved 22.5%. Revenue for 2012 achieved 104.8%, up from 94.7% in 2011; Revenue as a percentage of GDP reached13.7% in 2012 compared to 13% in 2011.

comment.narrative: Improved revenue administration enable better collection of both tax and non-tax revenues.

title.narrative: MEF provides line ministries with a framework for budgeting that strengthens links between resource inputs and outputs/results.

baseline.value: The accountability for and proportion of budgets to be allocated to service unit activities not identified in budget.

target.value: Programme Oriented and Accountable Output/Activity Based Budgets implemented across all Ministries

actual.value: Budget reform implementation plan has been sent to the Prime Minister for approval. Program based budgeting has been deepened inline ministries and is in the process of scaling up with a series of training workshopson guideline for program budgeting at sectorlevel.

title.narrative: Policy agenda implemented through implementation of MTBF and MTEF/Programe Budgeting in Line Ministries

baseline.value: Fragmented and partial budget process for example between recurrent and capital. No forum for substantive discussion about budgetpriorities and justification

target.value: MEF produces GFS classified, comprehensive unitary budget oriented toward achieving program results.

actual.value: Medium term expenditure framework (MTEF) 2013-2015 has been prepared to provide a basis for the preparation of medium term budgetpolicy.

title.narrative: Strengthen the regulatory framework for internal audit and build internal audit capacity.

baseline.value: Internal audit in two ministries only. Low levels of regulatory compliance (less than 25 instititutions) and capacity relating tointernal audit.

target.value: Internal audit units established at each line ministries. Each internal audit unit produced audit reports for their respectiveminister.

actual.value: All line ministries (12 state owned enterprises). Internal audit review has been done at 27 line ministries and 12 publicenterprises.

comment.narrative: Preparation for IT-based audit is underway in preparation for FMIS implementation. Software IDEA has been provided to IAD of MEF.Policy paper for internal management to support FMIS was developed.

title.narrative: Strengthened management and utilisation of MEF HR as measured by improved productivity. performance and conditions of service for skilled personnel.

baseline.value: Low productivity, high levels of absence, weak retention of skilled staff due to inadequate incentives (average salaries less thanUS$50 per month).

target.value: Pay levels increased to between US$150-400.

actual.value: The government increased salary of civil servants in the lowest category by nearly 40%. Currently,the basic salary plus allowancefor category D civil servant is US$61. Other categories will receive a 20% increase (continuation of current government mandate).

comment.narrative: The government revised pay scale of the lowest category of civil servant (D) in Royal Decree NS/RKT/0113/120.

title.narrative: Improved accountability and internal control systems result in strengthened compliance and transparency in the mobilization and useof public resources.

baseline.value: Substantial inconsistencies between final TOFE (mid-following year) for the year and interim report produced at end of the year.Average delay in producing in-year TOFE (2001-2003) was 3-4 weeks.

target.value: Inconsistencies between final TOFE and interim report at end of financial year eliminated under FMIS.

actual.value: Reduced inconsistencies between the final TOFE and interim report. But TOEF report has been somehow delayed longer.

comment.narrative: Inconsistencies between the final TOFE and interim report have been reduced. But TOEF report has been somehow delayed longer.

title.narrative: More reliable and comprehensive Budget Monitoring and Accounting data reported. MEF's & LM management can use data for better decision making.

baseline.value: Weak legal framework for supply of some forms of data to MEF. Accounting data (Non Tax Rev/DP Projects) suffers from same lack ofcompleteness.

target.value: Legal framework for supply of data to MEF established. FMIS implemented.

actual.value: The government adopted a budget classification and chart of accounts based on international standards such as International PublicSector Accounting Standards (IPSAS), Classification of the Functions of Government (COFOG) and Government Finance Statistics(GFS),enhanced cash management, and consolidated bank accounts within the Treasury Single Account (TSA), all of which are importantprerequisites for the implementation of FMIS. The acquistion of the FMIS has moved into the second phase of the two stagecompetitive bidding.
